Chapter 2 - Ownership and Lifetimes
TODO
Ownership - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
References
References - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Rust’s references in a nutshell:



                  Quote


There are two kinds of reference:

Shared reference: &amp;
Mutable reference: &amp;mut

Which obey the following rules:

A reference cannot outlive its referent
A mutable reference cannot be aliased
A short lifetime cannot be coerced into a longer one.


Aliasing
Aliasing - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)

Variables and pointers alias if they refer to overlapping regions of memory.

Lifetimes
Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)

Lifetimes are named regions of code that a reference must be valid for. … Types which contain references (or pretend to) may also be tagged with lifetimes


In most of our examples, the lifetimes will coincide with scopes.


A reference (sometimes called a borrow) is alive from the place it is created to its last use.

For instance, the references in this program:
let x = 0;
let y = &amp;x;
let z = &amp;y;
will have the following lifetimes &#039;a, &#039;b and &#039;c, which correspond to the scopes of their variables x, y and `z:
&#039;a: {
    let x: i32 = 0;
    &#039;b: {
		let y: &amp;&#039;b i32 = &amp;&#039;b x;
	        &#039;c: {
	            let z: &amp;&#039;c &amp;&#039;b i32 = &amp;&#039;c y;
	        }
	    }
}
Examples where the lifetime rules are violated:

“A reference cannot outlive its referent”

See example: Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)


“A mutable reference cannot be aliased”

See example: Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)



Furthermore, lifetimes may vary in each branch of a condition, or may have holes if the variable is reassigned the same reference later in the program: Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Minimising Lifetimes
Rust always tries to minimise the lifetimes of references.
In this example, the lifetime of the reference x will get minimised from &#039;d to &#039;b&#039; to avoid the overlap of lifetimes &#039;b and &#039;c:
let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3];
let x = &amp;data[0];
println!(&quot;{}&quot;, x);
data.push(4);
&#039;a: {
    let mut data: Vec&lt;i32&gt; = vec![1, 2, 3];
    &#039;d: {
	    &#039;b: {
	        let x: &amp;&#039;b i32 = Index::index::&lt;&#039;b&gt;(&amp;&#039;b data, 0);
	        println!(&quot;{}&quot;, x);
	    }
		&#039;c: {
			Vec::push(&amp;&#039;c mut data, 4);
		}
	}
}
Unless x is a struct that implements a destructor, in which case x will also be used at the end of scope, as illustrated in: Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Expanding Lifetimes
Rust can expand the lifetime of a reference unless it crosses the function boundary.
In this example, the lifetime of the reference y has been expanded from &#039;c to &#039;b:
let x = 0;
let z;
let y = &amp;x;
z = y;
&#039;a: {
    let x: i32 = 0;
    &#039;b: {
        let z: &amp;&#039;b i32;
        &#039;c: {
            let y: &amp;&#039;b i32 = &amp;&#039;b x;
            z = y;
        }
    }
}
Limits of Lifetimes
Limits of Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Examples where the lifetime rules are respected but Rust is unable to understand it due to the limitation of its syntax/borrow checker:

Lifetime elision rules may relate two references inappropriately.

See example: Limits of Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)


Lifetimes of the reference matched against in a match block conservatively extends to the end of the block.

See example: Limits of Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)



Lifetime Elision
Lifetime Elision - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)



                  Quote


Elision rules are as follows:

Each elided lifetime in input position becomes a distinct lifetime parameter.
If there is exactly one input lifetime position (elided or not), that lifetime is assigned to all elided output lifetimes.
If there are multiple input lifetime positions, but one of them is &amp;self or &amp;mut self, the lifetime of self is assigned to all elided output lifetimes.
Otherwise, it is an error to elide an output lifetime.


Most of the rules are straightforward, but check the examples just in case: Lifetime Elision - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Unbounded Lifetimes
Unbounded Lifetimes - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
A lifetime parameter &lt;&#039;a&gt; introduced at function/struct definition asserts that &#039;a outlives that function/struct’s lifetime: Explicit annotation - Rust By Example (rust-lang.org)
But unless such &#039;a gets associated with a lifetime, it becomes unbounded. For instance:

A function with return value but without a lifetime parameter in the input position.
A struct without any reference field but with a lifetime parameter.

In this example, get_str produces an unbounded lifetime parameter &#039;a:
fn get_str&lt;&#039;a&gt;(s: *const String) -&gt; &amp;&#039;a str {
    unsafe { &amp;*s }
}
Higher-Rank Trait Bounds
Higher-Rank Trait Bounds - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)

How on earth are we supposed to express the lifetimes on F’s trait bound? We need to provide some lifetime there, but the lifetime we care about can’t be named until we enter the body of call!

HRTB is slightly more complicated than this. For details, check Early and Late Lifetime Binding.
Subtyping and Variance
Subtyping and Variance - The Rustonomicon (rust-lang.org)
Rust does not have the notion of subtyping for normal types, only lifetimes.
Subtraits/supertraits are not part of subtyping - subtraits simply copy all the specs of their supertraits.

Engineering/Programming-Languages/TypeSc.content:
Any Type
The any type is handy but it comes at a cost - it is essentially bypassing the type check and can give unexpected results:
type ToString1&lt;T extends [any]&gt; = `${T[0]}`
type ToString2&lt;T extends { key: any }&gt; = `${T[&quot;key&quot;]}`
type ToString3&lt;T extends Record&lt;any, any&gt;&gt; = {
  [P in keyof T as P]: `${T[P]}`
}
type ToString4&lt;T extends Record&lt;any, any&gt;&gt; = {
  [P in keyof T as `${T[P]}`]: P
}

type Type1 = ToString1&lt;[true]&gt; // true - not &quot;true&quot;
type Type2 = ToString2&lt;{ key: true }&gt; // true - not &quot;true&quot;
type Type3 = ToString3&lt;{ key: true }&gt; // { key: true }
type Type4 = ToString4&lt;{ key: true }&gt; // {} - not { true: &quot;key&quot; }
Replacing any with unknown gives a compiler error, so these behaviours are really undefined i.e anything can happen.

Compute
Sometimes intersections remain in the syntactic form - we can expand this by mapping over its keys, as seen in this Compute&lt;T&gt; example:
type Compute&lt;T&gt; = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] }

type AppendToObject1&lt;T, U extends string, V&gt; = T &amp; { [K in U]: V}
type AppendToObject2&lt;T, U extends string, V&gt; = Compute&lt;T &amp; { [K in U]: V}&gt;

type Test1 = {
  key: &#039;cat&#039;
  value: &#039;green&#039;
}
type TestExpect1 = {
  key: &#039;cat&#039;
  value: &#039;green&#039;
  home: boolean
}

type Type1 = AppendToObject1&lt;Test1, &#039;home&#039;, boolean&gt; // Test1 &amp; { home: boolean }
type Type2 = AppendToObject2&lt;Test1, &#039;home&#039;, boolean&gt; // { key: &#039;cat&#039;; value: &#039;green&#039;; home: boolean; }

Index Signatures
github.com/type-challenges/type-challenges/issues/14662#issuecomment-1837202015
By default, the keys of an object type will have literal types e.g. &quot;foo&quot;, but this can be overridden by specifying the new types using index signatures:
type Foo = {
	[key: string]: any;
	foo(): void;
}

type Type1 = keyof Foo // string | &quot;foo&quot;, not &quot;key&quot; | &quot;foo&quot;

In fact, the record types can be seen as a special kind of object types with a single index signature:
type RecordType = {
	[key: string]: number;
}

type ComlexRecordType = {
	[key: Exclude&lt;string, &quot;&quot;&gt;]: any;
	[key: number]: any;
	key1: string;
	key2: boolean;	
}

Intersection and Union
Objects &amp; Records — Type-Level TypeScript (type-level-typescript.com)
The following rules hold:
keyof (A &amp; B) = (keyof A) | (keyof B)
keyof (A | B) = (keyof A) &amp; (keyof B)

type A = { a: string };
type KeyOfA = keyof A; // =&gt; &#039;a&#039;

type B = { b: number };
type KeyOfB = keyof B; // =&gt; &#039;b&#039;

type C = A &amp; B;
type KeyOfC = keyof C; // =&gt; &#039;a&#039; | &#039;b&#039;
This holds because A contains objects with property a: string plus any extra properties, and similarly for B, so A &amp; B is precisely identical to type { a: string; b: number }.
type A = { a: string; c: boolean };
type KeyOfA = keyof A; // =&gt; &#039;a&#039; | &#039;c&#039;

type B = { b: number; c: boolean };
type KeyOfB = keyof B; // =&gt; &#039;b&#039; | &#039;c&#039;

type C = A | B;
type KeyOfC = keyof C; // =&gt; &#039;c&#039;
On the contrary, A | B is not identical to type { c: boolean } - if we draw a Venn diagram with each set corresponding to types { a: string }, { b: number } and { c: boolean } respectively, we can clearly see C strictly contains A | B.
But remember that keyof T is defined to be the known keys of T. In this case, the known key of A | B is c: boolean,  in a sense that this is present in both A and B.

Void Type
A variable of type void can only be assigned values of type void or undefined:
const a: void = 1 // error
const b: void = undefined // ok

function f(): void {}
const c: void = f() // ok
which makes sense, because in JavaScript functions without return simply returns undefined.
In contrast, a function whose return type is void can be assigned any function whose parameter types are identical but returns any type T:
function g(): void {}
function h(): number { return 0; }

const a: () =&gt; void = g // ok
const b: () =&gt; void = h // still ok

const c: () =&gt; undefined = g // error
const d: () =&gt; undefined = h // error

void is not the same as undefined:
function forEach1&lt;T&gt;(arr: T[], fn: (a: T) =&gt; void): void {
	for (const a of arr) fn(a);
}
function forEach2&lt;T&gt;(arr: T[], fn: (a: T) =&gt; undefined): void {
	for (const a of arr) fn(a);
}

const arr1 = [];
forEach1([1, 2, 3], (a) =&gt; arr1.push(a)); // ok

const arr2 = [];
forEach2([1, 2, 3], (a) =&gt; arr2.push(a)); // error - (1)

In (1), Array.push() returns the pushed value of type number, which is not assignable to undefined.

nor unknown:
function forEach3&lt;T&gt;(arr: T[], fn: (a: T) =&gt; void): void {
	for (const a of arr) {
		const ret = fn(a); // `ret` is of type `void`.
	    if (ret instanceof Number) { // error - (2)
	      console.log(ret);
	    }
	}
}
function forEach4&lt;T&gt;(arr: T[], fn: (a: T) =&gt; unknown): void {
	for (const a of arr) {
		const ret = fn(a); // `ret` is of type `unknown`.
	    if (ret instanceof Number) { // ok - (3)
	      console.log(ret);
	    }
	}
}

In (2), the LHS of instanceof must be an object.


In (3), fn of return type unknown does not imply that we are not interested in its return value, so it’s examinable at the runtime. This behaviour is probably not what we want.

